{:correct? true, :passed 7, :total-tests 7, :q-num 1, :trace [{:iteration 0, :thinking "Need to generate palindromic numbers efficiently as a lazy sequence. The key insight is to generate palindromes by length and by half, rather than checking every number.\n\nFor a palindrome of length L:\n- If L is odd: take a number of length (L+1)/2, reverse all but last digit, append. E.g., half=123, palindrome=12321.\n- If L is even: take a number of length L/2, reverse it, append. E.g., half=12, palindrome=1221.\n\nFor starting at n, I need to figure out what length and half to start at.\n\nLet me think about generating all palindromes in order. They go: 0-9 (1-digit), 11,22,...,99 (2-digit), 101,111,...,999 (3-digit), 1001,... (4-digit), etc.\n\nApproach: generate palindromes by length. For each length, iterate through the \"half\" values. For length 1: halves are 0-9. For length 2: halves are 1-9 (leading digit can't be 0 for multi-digit). Actually wait - for length 2, half is 1-9, and we mirror the digit. For length 3, half is 10-99, and we mirror without the last digit.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully:\n\nLength 1: digits 0-9 → palindromes 0-9\nLength 2: for d from 1 to 9 → 11*d (11, 22, ..., 99)\nLength 3: for h from 10 to 99 → h*10 + (reverse of h without last digit) = h*10 + (h/10)\n  So 10→101, 11→111, ..., 99→999\nLength 4: for h from 10 to 99 → h*100 + reverse(h)\n  10→1001, 11→1111, ..., 99→9999\nLength 5: for h from 100 to 999 → h*100 + reverse(h without last digit)\n  100→10001, etc.\n\nGeneral pattern:\n- For even length 2k: half ranges from 10^(k-1) to 10^k - 1. Palindrome = half * 10^k + reverse(half).\n- For odd length 2k+1 (k>=1): half ranges from 10^(k-1) to 10^k - 1... wait, let me reconsider.\n\nActually, let me think of it differently. Let the \"half\" be the prefix.\n\nFor length 1: prefix = 0..9, palindrome = prefix\nFor length 2: prefix = 1..9, palindrome = prefix * 11 (i.e., prefix * 10 + prefix)\nFor length 3: prefix = 10..99, palindrome = prefix * 10 + (prefix / 10) [integer division]\nFor length 4: prefix = 10..99, palindrome = prefix * 100 + reverse(prefix)\nFor length 5: prefix = 100..999, palindrome = prefix * 100 + (reverse(prefix) / 10)\nFor length 6: prefix = 100..999, palindrome = prefix * 1000 + reverse(prefix)\n\nPattern for even length L=2k: prefix has k digits (from 10^(k-1) to 10^k-1). Palindrome = prefix * 10^k + reverse(prefix).\nPattern for odd length L=2k+1 (k>=1): prefix has k+1 digits (from 10^k to 10^(k+1)-1). Palindrome = prefix * 10^k + (reverse(prefix) / 10).\n\nWait, let me verify:\n- L=3, k=1: prefix 10..99 (2 digits = k+1). Palindrome = prefix * 10 + reverse(prefix)/10. For prefix=10: 10*10 + 01/10 = 100 + 0 = 100? That's wrong. Should be 101.\n\nreverse(10) = 01 = 1. 1/10 = 0 in integer division. That gives 100, not 101.\n\nHmm. Let me reconsider. reverse(10) should give 1 (dropping leading zeros). So prefix * 10^k + reverse(prefix) / 10^... no.\n\nFor odd length: we want to take the prefix, then append the reverse of the prefix WITHOUT the last digit.\nprefix = 123, L=5, k=2. We want 12321. That's prefix * 10^k + reverse(prefix / 10) = 123 * 100 + reverse(12) = 12300 + 21 = 12321. Yes!\n\nFor prefix = 10, L=3, k=1: 10 * 10 + reverse(1) = 100 + 1 = 101. Correct!\n\nSo:\n- Even length L=2k: palindrome = prefix * 10^k + reverse(prefix), prefix from 10^(k-1) to 10^k-1\n- Odd length L=2k+1 (k>=1): palindrome = prefix * 10^k + reverse(prefix / 10), prefix from 10^k to 10^(k+1)-1\n- Length 1: special case, 0-9\n\nNow for starting at n:\n1. Check if n itself is a palindrome. If so, start there.\n2. Otherwise, find the first palindrome >= n.\n\nTo find the first palindrome >= n, I can:\n- Determine the length of n\n- Generate the palindrome for the prefix of n\n- If that palindrome >= n, use it\n- Otherwise, increment the prefix and generate the next palindrome\n- If the prefix overflows (e.g., 99 → 100), move to the next length\n\nThen from that starting point, generate all subsequent palindromes.\n\nLet me code this up. I need a reverse-number function.\n\n```clojure\n(fn [n]\n  (let [rev (fn [x]\n              (loop [v x r 0]\n                (if (zero? v) r\n                    (recur (quot v 10) (+ (* r 10) (rem v 10))))))\n        ;; Generate palindrome from prefix and length info\n        ;; :even means L=2k, prefix is k digits\n        ;; :odd means L=2k+1, prefix is k+1 digits\n        pal-even (fn [prefix k] (+ (* prefix (long (Math/pow 10 k))) (rev prefix)))\n        pal-odd  (fn [prefix k] (+ (* prefix (long (Math/pow 10 k))) (rev (quot prefix 10))))\n        ;; Starting palindrome >= n\n        start-pal (fn [n]\n                    (if (<= n 0) 0\n                        (let [s (str n)\n                              len (count s)\n                              half-len (quot len 2)]\n                          (if (= len 1)\n                            (if (<= n 9) n 11)  ;; single digit\n                            (if (even? len)\n                              ;; even length\n                              (let [prefix (Long/parseLong (subs s 0 half-len))\n                                    p (pal-even prefix half-len)]\n                                (if (>= p n) p\n                                  (let [np (inc prefix)]\n                                    (if (= np (long (Math/pow 10 half-len)))\n                                      (pal-odd (long (Math/pow 10 half-len)) half-len)\n                                      (pal-even np half-len)))))\n                              ;; odd length\n                              (let [prefix (Long/parseLong (subs s 0 (inc half-len)))\n                                    p (pal-odd prefix half-len)]\n                                (if (>= p n) p\n                                  (let [np (inc prefix)]\n                                    (if (= np (long (Math/pow 10 (inc half-len))))\n                                      (pal-even (long (Math/pow 10 half-len)) half-len)\n                                      (pal-odd np half-len))))))))))\n        ;; Generate all palindromes starting from length info\n        gen-pals (fn [len prefix]\n                   (lazy-seq\n                    (let [k (quot len 2)]\n                      (if (even? len)\n                        (let [p (pal-even prefix k)\n                              max-pref (dec (long (Math/pow 10 k)))]\n                          (cons p\n                                (if (< prefix max-pref)\n                                  (gen-pals len (inc prefix))\n                                  ;; Move to next length (odd)\n                                  (gen-pals (inc len) (long (Math/pow 10 k))))))\n                        ;; odd length\n                        (let [p (pal-odd prefix k)\n                              max-pref (dec (long (Math/pow 10 (inc k))))]\n                          (cons p\n                                (if (< prefix max-pref)\n                                  (gen-pals len (inc prefix))\n                                  ;; Move to next length (even)\n                                  (gen-pals (inc len) (long (Math/pow 10 k))))))))))\n        s (start-pal n)\n        s-str (str s)\n        s-len (count s-str)\n        s-k (quot s-len 2)\n        s-prefix (if (even? s-len)\n                   (Long/parseLong (subs s-str 0 s-k))\n                   (Long/parseLong (subs s-str 0 (inc s-k))))]\n    (gen-pals s-len s-prefix)))\n```\n\nWait, there's a subtlety. For length 1, the first element should be 0 if n <= 0. But I handle n=0 as start-pal returning 0. Then gen-pals with len=1, prefix=0... but my gen-pals doesn't handle len=1.\n\nLet me handle length 1 separately. For length 1, palindromes are 0-9. Then move to length 2.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the structure. Maybe I should handle lengths 1 and 2 as special cases, then use the general pattern for length >= 3.\n\nOr better: let me redefine to avoid Math/pow (which returns double and could have precision issues for large numbers). I'll use exponentiation via loop.\n\nAlso, for the test with 1234550000, we need to handle large numbers. Math/pow should be fine for the exponents involved (max ~10), but let me use integer arithmetic to be safe.\n\nLet me also reconsider: the test `(first (__ (* 111111111 111111111)))` = `(* 111111111 111111111)` = 12345678987654321. That's a 17-digit number. Is it a palindrome? 12345678987654321 - yes it is! Length 17, odd.\n\nSo I need to handle up to 17-digit numbers. That's fine, long can handle up to 18 digits.\n\nLet me rewrite more carefully:\n\n```clojure\n(fn [n]\n  (let [pow10 (fn [k] (long (Math/pow 10 k)))  ;; fine for k <= 18\n        rev (fn [x] ...)\n        pal-even (fn [prefix k] ...)\n        pal-odd (fn [prefix k] ...)\n        ...])\n```\n\nActually, for large numbers, I should be careful. `(* 111111111 111111111)` = 12345678987654321. Let me verify that fits in a long. Long max is about 9.2 * 10^18. So yes.\n\nLet me also think about the start-pal for n=0. It should return 0.\n\nFor the edge case where n is exactly a power of 10 minus 1, like n=99: start-pal should return 99 (which is a palindrome). Then next should be 101.\n\nLet me trace through start-pal for n=99:\n- s=\"99\", len=2, half-len=1, even\n- prefix=9, p=pal-even(9,1)=9*10+9=99\n- 99>=99, so return 99. Good.\n\nThen gen-pals(2, 9):\n- k=1, even, p=99, max-pref=9\n- prefix >= max-pref, so move to len=3, prefix=pow10(1)=10\n- gen-pals(3, 10): k=1, odd, p=pal-odd(10,1)=10*10+rev(1)=100+1=101. \n\nLet me trace for n=162:\n- s=\"162\", len=3, half-len=1, odd\n- prefix=16, p=pal-odd(16,1)=16*10+rev(1)=160+1=161\n- 161 < 162, so np=17\n- 17 != pow10(2)=100, so pal-odd(17,1)=17*10+rev(1)=170+1=171. \n\nAnd gen-pals(3, 17) should give 171, 181, 191, then move to len=4...\n\ngen-pals(3, 17): k=1, odd, p=171, max-pref=99. 17<99, so gen-pals(3,18): p=181. etc.\ngen-pals(3, 19): p=191, 19<99, gen-pals(3,20): p=202. Wait, pal-odd(20,1)=20*10+rev(2)=200+2=202. Correct!\n\nFor n=1234550000:\n- s=\"1234550000\", len=10, half-len=5, even\n- prefix=12345, p=pal-even(12345,5)=12345*100000+rev(12345)=1234500000+54321=1234554321\n- 1234554321 >= 1234550000, so return 1234554321. \n\nNow for n=0: start-pal(0) should return 0. Then gen-pals... I need to handle len=1.\n\nFor len=1, prefix from 0 to 9. After 9, move to len=2 with prefix=1.\n\nLet me add special handling for len=1 in gen-pals:\n\n```clojure\ngen-pals (fn [len prefix]\n           (lazy-seq\n            (cond\n              (= len 1)\n              (let [p prefix]\n                (cons p (if (< prefix 9) (gen-pals 1 (inc prefix))\n                                   (gen-pals 2 1))))\n              (even? len) ...\n              :else ...)))\n```\n\nAnd start-pal for n<=9: return n.\nFor n=0, len=1, start-pal returns 0, gen-pals(1,0) → 0,1,2,...,9, then gen-pals(2,1) → 11,22,...,99, etc.\n\nWait, but start-pal also needs to handle single-digit n properly. If n=5, start-pal returns 5, gen-pals(1,5) → 5,6,7,8,9, then gen-pals(2,1) → 11,...\n\nThat looks correct.\n\nWhat about start-pal for n=10?\n- s=\"10\", len=2, half-len=1, even\n- prefix=1, p=pal-even(1,1)=11\n- 11>=10, return 11. Good.\n\nWhat about n=100?\n- s=\"100\", len=3, half-len=1, odd\n- prefix=10, p=pal-odd(10,1)=101\n- 101>=100, return 101. Good.\n\nWhat about n=999?\n- s=\"999\", len=3, half-len=1, odd\n- prefix=99, p=pal-odd(99,1)=99*10+rev(9)=990+9=999\n- 999>=999, return 999. Good.\n\nNext: gen-pals(3, 99): k=1, odd, p=999, max-pref=99. 99>=99, move to len=4, prefix=pow10(1)=10.\ngen-pals(4, 10): k=2, even, p=pal-even(10,2)=10*100+rev(10)=1000+1=1001. Correct!\n\nNow the tricky test: `(nth (__ 0) 10101)` should be 9102019.\n\nThat's the 10102nd element (0-indexed). That's a lot of elements to generate but since it's lazy, it should be fine as long as generation is O(1) per element.\n\nLet me also consider: for very large n like (* 111111111 111111111) = 12345678987654321:\n- s=\"12345678987654321\", len=17, half-len=8, odd\n- prefix = parseLong(\"123456789\") = 123456789\n- p = pal-odd(123456789, 8) = 123456789 * 10^8 + rev(12345678)\n- rev(12345678) = 87654321\n- 123456789 * 100000000 = 12345678900000000\n- + 87654321 = 12345678987654321. Correct!\n\nOK, I think the algorithm is sound. Let me also think about `pow10` - for k up to 8, Math/pow should be fine (returns exact doubles for small powers of 10). But to be safe, let me use a loop-based version:\n\n```clojure\npow10 (fn [k] (loop [i k r 1] (if (zero? i) r (recur (dec i) (* r 10)))))\n```\n\nNow let me also consider the `str` approach for parsing the prefix. For very large numbers, str should work fine.\n\nActually, I realize I can avoid string parsing for the prefix. Given n and length len, I can compute the prefix as:\n- even len: prefix = quot(n, 10^(len/2))\n- odd len: prefix = quot(n, 10^(len/2))\n\nWait: for len=3, half-len=1. prefix = quot(n, 10^1) = quot(n, 10). For n=162, prefix=16. For n=999, prefix=99. Correct.\n\nFor len=10, half-len=5. prefix = quot(n, 10^5). For n=1234550000, prefix = quot(1234550000, 100000) = 12345. Correct.\n\nFor len=17, half-len=8. prefix = quot(n, 10^8). For n=12345678987654321, prefix = 123456789. Correct.\n\nSo I can avoid str entirely:\n\n```clojure\nstart-pal (fn [n]\n            (cond\n              (<= n 0) 0\n              (<= n 9) n\n              :else\n              (let [len (count (str n))\n                    k (quot len 2)\n                    pw (pow10 k)]\n                (if (even? len)\n                  (let [prefix (quot n pw)\n                        p (+ (* prefix pw) (rev prefix))]\n                    (if (>= p n) p\n                      (let [np (inc prefix)]\n                        (if (= np (pow10 k))\n                          ;; overflow to odd length\n                          (let [pw2 pw]  ;; same k\n                            (+ (* np pw2) (rev (quot np 10))))\n                          (+ (* np pw) (rev np))))))\n                  ;; odd\n                  (let [prefix (quot n pw)\n                        p (+ (* prefix pw) (rev (quot prefix 10)))]\n                    (if (>= p n) p\n                      (let [np (inc prefix)]\n                        (if (= np (pow10 (inc k)))\n                          ;; overflow to even length\n                          (let [pw2 (* pw 10)]  ;; k+1\n                            (+ (* (pow10 k) pw2) (rev (pow10 k))))\n                          (+ (* np pw) (rev (quot np 10)))))))))))\n```\n\nHmm, this is getting complicated with the overflow cases. Let me trace through:\n\nFor even length, prefix overflows: e.g., len=2, k=1, prefix=9→10, and 10=pow10(1). We need to move to len=3 (odd), prefix=pow10(1)=10.\npal-odd(10, 1) = 10 * 10 + rev(1) = 101. \n\nFor odd length, prefix overflows: e.g., len=3, k=1, prefix=99→100, and 100=pow10(2). We need to move to len=4 (even), prefix=pow10(1)=10.\npal-even(10, 2) = 10 * 100 + rev(10) = 1001. \n\nSo in the overflow case for even → odd: new prefix = pow10(k), new k = k (same), generate odd palindrome.\npal-odd(pow10(k), k) = pow10(k) * pow10(k) + rev(pow10(k-1)) = 10^(2k) + 1.\n\nFor k=1: 100 + 1 = 101. Correct (next after 99).\nFor k=2: 10000 + 1 = 10001. Correct (next after 9999).\n\nIn the overflow case for odd → even: new prefix = pow10(k), new k = k+1 (len increased by 1, now even), generate even palindrome.\npal-even(pow10(k), k+1) = pow10(k) * pow10(k+1) + rev(pow10(k)) = 10^(2k+1) + 1.\n\nFor k=1: 10 * 100 + 1 = 1001. Correct (next after 999).\nFor k=2: 100 * 1000 + 1 = 100001. Correct (next after 99999).\n\nWait, rev(pow10(k)): pow10(1)=10, rev(10)=1. pow10(2)=100, rev(100)=1. So rev(pow10(k)) = 1 for k>=1. That makes sense since pow10(k) is 1 followed by k zeros, reversed is 1 (ignoring leading zeros).\n\nOK let me simplify the overflow cases:\n\nEven overflow (prefix goes from 10^k - 1 to 10^k): return 10^(2k) + 1\nOdd overflow (prefix goes from 10^(k+1) - 1 to 10^(k+1)): return 10^(2k+1) + 1\n\nHmm, but those are just pal-odd(pow10(k), k) and pal-even(pow10(k), k+1) respectively. Let me just use the pal functions.\n\nActually, I realize I can simplify by just computing the palindrome and checking. Let me restructure:\n\n```clojure\n(fn [n]\n  (let [pow10 (fn [k] ...)\n        rev (fn [x] ...)\n        make-pal (fn [prefix len]\n                   (let [k (quot len 2)]\n                     (if (even? len)\n                       (+ (* prefix (pow10 k)) (rev prefix))\n                       (+ (* prefix (pow10 k)) (rev (quot prefix 10))))))\n        next-pal (fn [prefix len]\n                   (let [k (quot len 2)\n                         max-pref (if (even? len) (pow10 k) (pow10 (inc k)))\n                         np (inc prefix)]\n                     (if (= np max-pref)\n                       ;; move to next length\n                       (if (even? len)\n                         ;; even → odd: same k, prefix = pow10(k)\n                         [(pow10 k) (inc len)]\n                         ;; odd → even: k stays same conceptually but len increases\n                         [(pow10 k) (inc len)])\n                       [np len])))\n        start (if (<= n 0) [0 1]\n                (let [s (str n)\n                      len (count s)\n                      k (quot len 2)\n                      pw (pow10 k)\n                      prefix (if (even? len) (quot n pw) (quot n pw))]\n                  ;; But wait, for odd len, prefix has k+1 digits, and we divide by pw=10^k\n                  ;; which gives us the first k+1 digits. Correct.\n                  (let [p (make-pal prefix len)]\n                    (if (>= p n) [prefix len]\n                        (next-pal prefix len)))))\n        gen (fn [[prefix len]]\n              (lazy-seq\n               (cons (make-pal prefix len)\n                     (gen (next-pal prefix len)))))]\n    (gen start)))\n```\n\nWait, but start for n=0 gives [0 1]. gen([0 1]) → make-pal(0, 1) = ... k=0, even, 0 * 1 + rev(0) = 0. Then next-pal(0, 1): k=0, max-pref=pow10(0)=1, np=1, 1=1 so move to next len. even→odd: [pow10(0)=1, 2]. gen([1, 2]): make-pal(1, 2) = 1*10+rev(1)=11. next-pal(1, 2): k=1, max-pref=pow10(1)=10, np=2, 2≠10, [2, 2]. make-pal(2, 2)=22. Etc. But we skipped 1-9!\n\nThe issue is that for len=1, the prefix range is 0-9, not 0 to pow10(0)=1. Length 1 is special.\n\nLet me handle it differently. Instead of using the general make-pal for len=1, handle it separately:\n\n```clojure\ngen (fn [[prefix len]]\n      (lazy-seq\n       (if (= len 1)\n         (cons prefix\n               (if (< prefix 9)\n                 (gen [(inc prefix) 1])\n                 (gen [1 2])))\n         (cons (make-pal prefix len)\n               (gen (next-pal prefix len))))))\n```\n\nAnd start for n<=9: [n 1]. For n=0: [0 1].\ngen([0, 1]) → 0, gen([1, 1]) → 1, ..., gen([9, 1]) → 9, gen([1, 2]) → make-pal(1, 2) = 11. \n\nBut wait, what about start for n=10? len=2, k=1, prefix=quot(10, 10)=1. make-pal(1, 2)=11. 11>=10. Start=[1, 2]. Correct.\n\nWhat about start for n=9? Since n<=9, start=[9, 1]. gen gives 9, then 11. Correct.\n\nWhat about start for n=11? len=2, k=1, prefix=1. make-pal(1, 2)=11. 11>=11. Start=[1, 2]. Correct.\n\nOK, I think this works. But there's another issue with start: for n=10, the prefix calculation. Let me re-check.\n\nFor n=10, len=2, even, k=1, pw=10. prefix = quot(10, 10) = 1. make-pal(1, 2) = 1*10 + rev(1) = 11. 11 >= 10. ✓\n\nFor n=100, len=3, odd, k=1, pw=10. prefix = quot(100, 10) = 10. make-pal(10, 3) = 10*10 + rev(1) = 101. 101 >= 100. ✓\n\nFor n=99, len=2, even, k=1, pw=10. prefix = 9. make-pal(9, 2) = 99. 99 >= 99. ✓\nnext-pal(9, 2): k=1, max-pref=10, np=10, 10=10, even→odd: [pow10(1)=10, 3]. make-pal(10, 3) = 101. ✓\n\nFor n=999, len=3, odd, k=1, pw=10. prefix = 99. make-pal(99, 3) = 99*10 + rev(9) = 999. ✓\nnext-pal(99, 3): k=1, max-pref=pow10(2)=100, np=100, 100=100, odd→even: [pow10(1)=10, 4]. make-pal(10, 4) = 10*100 + rev(10) = 1001. ✓\n\nFor n=1234550000, len=10, even, k=5, pw=100000. prefix = quot(1234550000, 100000) = 12345. make-pal(12345, 10) = 12345*100000 + rev(12345) = 1234500000 + 54321 = 1234554321. 1234554321 >= 1234550000. ✓\n\nNow for the big test: n = 12345678987654321, len=17, odd, k=8, pw=10^8=100000000. prefix = quot(12345678987654321, 100000000) = 123456789. make-pal(123456789, 17) = 123456789 * 10^8 + rev(12345678) = 12345678900000000 + 87654321 = 12345678987654321. ✓\n\nGreat, the algorithm works. Now let me also handle the edge case where n is negative. If n <= 0, start with [0, 1].\n\nLet me write the final code:\n\n```clojure\n(fn [n]\n  (let [pow10 (fn [k] (loop [i k r 1] (if (zero? i) r (recur (dec i) (*' r 10)))))\n        rev (fn [x] (loop [v x r 0] (if (zero? v) r (recur (quot v 10) (+ (*' r 10) (rem v 10))))))\n        make-pal (fn [prefix len]\n                   (let [k (quot len 2)]\n                     (if (even? len)\n                       (+' (*' prefix (pow10 k)) (rev prefix))\n                       (+' (*' prefix (pow10 k)) (rev (quot prefix 10))))))\n        next-state (fn [prefix len]\n                     (let [k (quot len 2)\n                           max-pref (if (even? len) (pow10 k) (pow10 (inc k)))\n                           np (inc prefix)]\n                       (if (= np max-pref)\n                         (if (even? len)\n                           [(pow10 k) (inc len)]\n                           [(pow10 k) (inc len)])\n                         [np len])))\n        start (if (<= n 0) [0 1]\n                (if (<= n 9) [n 1]\n                    (let [len (count (str n))\n                          k (quot len 2)\n                          pw (pow10 k)\n                          prefix (quot n pw)\n                          p (make-pal prefix len)]\n                      (if (>= p n) [prefix len]\n                          (next-state prefix len)))))\n        gen (fn [[prefix len]]\n              (lazy-seq\n               (if (= len 1)\n                 (cons prefix\n                       (if (< prefix 9)\n                         (gen [(inc prefix) 1])\n                         (gen [1 2])))\n                 (cons (make-pal prefix len)\n                       (gen (next-state prefix len))))))]\n    (gen start)))\n```\n\nWait, I'm using `*'` for arbitrary precision. But the problem says \"integer n\" and the tests use long values. Let me just use regular arithmetic since everything fits in a long. Actually, `*'` is fine and more robust.\n\nHmm, but actually in SCI, `*'` should work. Let me use regular `*` and `+` since all values fit in longs for this problem.\n\nActually wait, let me double-check: `(nth (__ 0) 10101)` should be 9102019. That's a 7-digit number. Fine.\n\nLet me also worry about performance. The test `(apply < (take 6666 (__ 9999999)))` generates 6666 palindromes starting from near 10000001. Each generation is O(digits) for the reverse operation, which is at most ~10. So 6666 * 10 = ~66K operations. That's fast.\n\nThe test `(set (take 199 (__ 0))) = (set (map #(first (__ %)) (range 0 10000)))` calls first on (__ %) for 10000 different values. Each call to start needs to compute the starting palindrome, which involves string conversion and some arithmetic. That's 10000 * ~10 = ~100K operations. Should be fine.\n\nOK let me also think about whether `*'` vs `*` matters. In Clojure, `*'` returns a BigInt when overflow would occur, `*` throws on overflow. Since we're dealing with numbers up to ~10^17, and long max is ~9.2*10^18, we're fine with regular `*`. But using `*'` is safer and shouldn't be slower.\n\nActually, I realize there might be a subtlety: `pow10` with `*'` will return a long for small values and a BigInt for large values. Mixing longs and BigInts in arithmetic is fine in Clojure but might be slightly slower. Since we don't need BigInts, let me use `*` and `+` with `long` coercion on pow10:\n\n```clojure\npow10 (fn [k] (loop [i k r (long 1)] (if (zero? i) r (recur (dec i) (* r (long 10))))))\n```\n\nThis ensures pow10 returns a long. And `*` and `+` on longs return longs. Fine.\n\nLet me write the final version and test it.\n\nActually, one more thing: the `str` call in start. For n = 12345678987654321, `(str n)` should work fine.\n\nLet me write and test:\n\n```clojure\n(def solution \"palindromic numbers generator\"\n  (fn [n]\n    (let [pow10 (fn [k] (loop [i k r 1] (if (zero? i) r (recur (dec i) (* r 10)))))\n          rev (fn [x] (loop [v x r 0] (if (zero? v) r (recur (quot v 10) (+ (* r 10) (rem v 10))))))\n          make-pal (fn [prefix len]\n                     (let [k (quot len 2)]\n                       (if (even? len)\n                         (+ (* prefix (pow10 k)) (rev prefix))\n                         (+ (* prefix (pow10 k)) (rev (quot prefix 10))))))\n          next-state (fn [prefix len]\n                       (let [k (quot len 2)\n                             max-pref (if (even? len) (pow10 k) (pow10 (inc k)))\n                             np (inc prefix)]\n                         (if (= np max-pref)\n                           [(pow10 k) (inc len)]\n                           [np len])))\n          start (if (<= n 0) [0 1]\n                  (if (<= n 9) [n 1]\n                      (let [len (count (str n))\n                            k (quot len 2)\n                            pw (pow10 k)\n                            prefix (quot n pw)\n                            p (make-pal prefix len)]\n                        (if (>= p n) [prefix len]\n                            (next-state prefix len)))))\n          gen (fn [prefix len]\n                (lazy-seq\n                 (if (= len 1)\n                   (cons prefix\n                         (if (< prefix 9)\n                           (gen (inc prefix) 1)\n                           (gen 1 2)))\n                   (cons (make-pal prefix len)\n                         (apply gen (next-state prefix len))))))]\n      (apply gen start))))\n```\n\nHmm, I changed gen to take two args instead of a vector for efficiency. Let me test this.\n\nActually, I realize I should be more careful. Let me just write it and test.", :executions [{:id 0, :code "(def solution \"palindromic numbers generator\"\n  (fn [n]\n    (let [pow10 (fn [k] (loop [i k r 1] (if (zero? i) r (recur (dec i) (* r 10)))))\n          rev (fn [x] (loop [v x r 0] (if (zero? v) r (recur (quot v 10) (+ (* r 10) (rem v 10))))))\n          make-pal (fn [prefix len]\n                     (let [k (quot len 2)]\n                       (if (even? len)\n                         (+ (* prefix (pow10 k)) (rev prefix))\n                         (+ (* prefix (pow10 k)) (rev (quot prefix 10))))))\n          next-state (fn [prefix len]\n                       (let [k (quot len 2)\n                             max-pref (if (even? len) (pow10 k) (pow10 (inc k)))\n                             np (inc prefix)]\n                         (if (= np max-pref)\n                           [(pow10 k) (inc len)]\n                           [np len])))\n          start (if (<= n 0) [0 1]\n                  (if (<= n 9) [n 1]\n                      (let [len (count (str n))\n                            k (quot len 2)\n                            pw (pow10 k)\n                            prefix (quot n pw)\n                            p (make-pal prefix len)]\n                        (if (>= p n) [prefix len]\n                            (next-state prefix len)))))\n          gen (fn [prefix len]\n                (lazy-seq\n                 (if (= len 1)\n                   (cons prefix\n                         (if (< prefix 9)\n                           (gen (inc prefix) 1)\n                           (gen 1 2)))\n                   (cons (make-pal prefix len)\n                         (apply gen (next-state prefix len))))))]\n      (apply gen start))))", :result nil, :stdout "", :stderr "", :error "ExceptionInfo: Unable to resolve symbol: gen", :execution-time-ms 14, :repaired? nil} {:id 1, :code "(assert (= (tak