 (max_pref = 10)\n- L=2: 1..9 (max_pref = 10)\n- L=3: 10..99 (max_pref = 100)\n- L=4: 10..99 (max_pref = 100)\n- L=5: 100..999 (max_pref = 1000)\n- L=6: 100..999 (max_pref = 1000)\n\nSo for L, k = L/2 (integer division):\n- Even L=2k: prefix from 10^(k-1) to 10^k - 1, i.e., max_pref = 10^k\n- Odd L=2k+1: prefix from 10^k to 10^(k+1) - 1, i.e., max_pref = 10^(k+1)\n\nWhen prefix reaches max_pref, move to next length.\n\nNext length transitions:\n- After L=1 (prefix 0..9), next is L=2, prefix=1\n- After L=2 (prefix 1..9), next is L=3, prefix=10\n- After L=3 (prefix 10..99), next is L=4, prefix=10\n- After L=4 (prefix 10..99), next is L=5, prefix=100\n\nSo when going from length L with prefix at max_pref:\n- If L is even (L=2k): next is L+1 (odd), prefix = 10^k\n- If L is odd (L=2k+1): next is L+1 (even), prefix = 10^k\n\nWait, let me verify:\n- L=1 (odd, k=0): max_pref=10. Next: L=2 (even), prefix=10^0=1. ✓\n- L=2 (even, k=1): max_pref=10. Next: L=3 (odd), prefix=10^1=10. ✓\n- L=3 (odd, k=1): max_pref=100. Next: L=4 (even), prefix=10^1=10. ✓\n- L=4 (even, k=2): max_pref=100. Next: L=5 (odd), prefix=10^2=100. ✓\n\nSo next state when prefix == max_pref:\n- new_len = len + 1\n- new_prefix = 10^(floor(len/2))\n\nFor make-pal:\n- k = floor(len/2)\n- Even: pal = prefix * 10^k + reverse(prefix)\n- Odd: pal = prefix * 10^k + reverse(floor(prefix/10))\n\nFor start state given n:\n- If n <= 0: start with prefix=0, len=1\n- Else: find appropriate (prefix, len) such that make-pal(prefix, len) >= n\n\nTo find starting state:\n1. Compute len = number of digits in n\n2. k = floor(len/2)\n3. prefix = floor(n / 10^k)\n4. p = make-pal(prefix, len)\n5. If p >= n, start = (prefix, len)\n6. Else, next-state(prefix, len)\n\nBut I also need to handle edge cases. If n=0, start at (0, 1). If n <= 9, start at (n, 1).\n\nActually let me just handle n <= 9 specially, and for n >= 10, use the digit-counting approach.\n\nWait, there's a subtlety. For n=10, len=2, k=1, prefix=floor(10/10)=1, p=11. 11 >= 10, so start=(1,2). Good.\n\nFor n=11, len=2, k=1, prefix=1, p=11. 11 >= 11, so start=(1,2). Good.\n\nFor n=12, len=2, k=1, prefix=1, p=11. 11 < 12, so next-state(1,2) = (2,2). Good.\n\nFor n=100, len=3, k=1, prefix=10, p=101. 101 >= 100, so start=(10,3). Good.\n\nFor n=999, len=3, k=1, prefix=99, p=999. 999 >= 999, so start=(99,3). Good.\n\nFor n=1000, len=4, k=2, prefix=10, p=1001. 1001 >= 1000, so start=(10,4). Good.\n\nNow let me write this with letfn:\n\n```clojure\n(fn [n]\n  (let [pow10 (fn [k] (long (Math/pow 10 k)))  ;; or manual loop\n        rev (fn [x] (loop [v x r 0] (if (zero? v) r (recur (quot v 10) (+ (* r 10) (rem v 10))))))\n        make-pal (fn [prefix len]\n                   (let [k (quot len 2)]\n                     (if (even? len)\n                       (+ (* prefix (pow10 k)) (rev prefix))\n                       (+ (* prefix (pow10 k)) (rev (quot prefix 10))))))\n        max-pref (fn [len] (let [k (quot len 2)]\n                             (if (even? len) (pow10 k) (pow10 (inc k)))))\n        next-state (fn [prefix len]\n                     (let [np (inc prefix)]\n                       (if (= np (max-pref len))\n                         [(pow10 (quot len 2)) (inc len)]\n                         [np len])))\n        start (if (<= n 0) [0 1]\n                (if (<= n 9) [n 1]\n                    (let [len (count (str n))\n                          k (quot len 2)\n                          pw (pow10 k)\n                          prefix (quot n pw)\n                          p (make-pal prefix len)]\n                      (if (>= p n) [prefix len]\n                          (next-state prefix len)))))]\n    (letfn [(gen [prefix len]\n              (lazy-seq\n               (cons (make-pal prefix len)\n                     (apply gen (next-state prefix len)))))]\n      (apply gen start))))\n```\n\nWait, but for len=1, prefix goes from 0 to 9, and max-pref(1) = 10^(0+1) = 10. So when prefix=9, next prefix=10=max-pref, so next-state = [10^(0), 2] = [1, 2]. Good.\n\nBut when n=0, start = [0, 1]. First palindrome = make-pal(0, 1) = 0*1 + rev(0/10) = 0 + 0 = 0. Good.\nThen next-state(0, 1) = [1, 1]. make-pal(1, 1) = 1. Good.\n...\nnext-state(9, 1) = [1, 2]. make-pal(1, 2) = 1*10 + rev(1) = 11. Good.\n\nLet me also check: n=162. len=3, k=1, pw=10, prefix=16, p = 16*10 + rev(1) = 160+1 = 161. 161 < 162, so next-state(16, 3) = [17, 3]. make-pal(17, 3) = 170 + rev(1) = 171. Good, matches expected.\n\nn=1234550000. Digits: let me count... 1234550000 is 10 digits. len=10, k=5, pw=100000, prefix = 1234550000/100000 = 12345. p = 12345 * 100000 + rev(12345) = 1234500000 + 54321 = 1234554321. 1234554321 >= 1234550000. Start = [12345, 10]. Good!\n\nOne concern: using Math/pow might give floating point issues for large numbers. Let me use a manual pow10 instead.\n\n```clojure\n(fn [n]\n  (let [pow10 (fn [k] (loop [i k r 1] (if (zero? i) r (recur (dec i) (* r 10)))))\n        rev (fn [x] (loop [v x r 0] (if (zero? v) r (recur (quot v 10) (+ (* r 10) (rem v 10))))))\n        make-pal (fn [prefix len]\n                   (let [k (quot len 2)]\n                     (if (even? len)\n                       (+ (* prefix (pow10 k)) (rev prefix))\n                       (+ (* prefix (pow10 k)) (rev (quot prefix 10))))))\n        max-pref (fn [len] (let [k (quot len 2)]\n                             (if (even? len) (pow10 k) (pow10 (inc k)))))\n        next-state (fn [prefix len]\n                     (let [np (inc prefix)]\n                       (if (= np (max-pref len))\n                         [(pow10 (quot len 2)) (inc len)]\n                         [np len])))\n        start (if (<= n 0) [0 1]\n                (if (<= n 9) [n 1]\n                    (let [len (count (str n))\n                          k (quot len 2)\n                          pw (pow10 k)\n                          prefix (quot n pw)\n                          p (make-pal prefix len)]\n                      (if (>= p n) [prefix len]\n                          (next-state prefix len)))))]\n    (letfn [(gen [prefix len]\n              (lazy-seq\n               (cons (make-pal prefix len)\n                     (apply gen (next-state prefix len)))))]\n      (apply gen start))))\n```\n\nLet me test this. The main issue before was using `gen` before it was defined. With `letfn`, this should be fixed.\n\nFor the nth test: (nth (solution 0) 10101) = 9102019. This would need to generate 10102 palindromes. With the efficient generation, this should be fast since each palindrome is O(1) to generate.\n\nLet me also verify the test with (* 111111111 111111111). That's 12345678987654321, which is a palindrome itself. So first of the sequence starting there should be itself.\n\nI think this solution is correct. Let me run it.", :executions [{:id 0, :code "(def solution \"palindromic numbers generator\"\n  (fn [n]\n    (let [pow10 (fn [k] (loop [i k r 1] (if (zero? i) r (recur (dec i) (* r 10)))))\n          rev (fn [x] (loop [v x r 0] (if (zero? v) r (recur (quot v 10) (+ (* r 10) (rem v 10))))))\n          make-pal (fn [prefix len]\n                     (let [k (quot len 2)]\n                       (if (even? len)\n                         (+ (* prefix (pow10 k)) (rev prefix))\n                         (+ (* prefix (pow10 k)) (rev (quot prefix 10))))))\n          max-pref (fn [len] (let [k (quot len 2)]\n                              (if (even? len) (pow10 k) (pow10 (inc k)))))\n          next-state (fn [prefix len]\n                       (let [np (inc prefix)]\n                         (if (= np (max-pref len))\n                           [(pow10 (quot len 2)) (inc len)]\n                           [np len])))\n          start (if (<= n 0) [0 1]\n                  (if (<= n 9) [n 1]\n                      (let [len (count (str n))\n                            k (quot len 2)\n                            pw (pow10 k)\n                            prefix (quot n pw)\n                            p (make-pal prefix len)]\n  